		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
				<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Callings</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From GwenWiki</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<a name=".CE.A9mni_System.E2.84.A2_Callings" id=".CE.A9mni_System.E2.84.A2_Callings"></a><h2> <span class="mw-headline"> Ωmni System™ Callings </span></h2>
<p>The Calling of a Mage is something like a pre-generated character. Callings are based on the Tradition of the mage and represent a starting "package" of skills a member of that Tradition would be expected to have. Six points have been left free for a mage to personalize their character. Additional changes may be made as described in the main Omni rulebook. Each Calling allows a player to make some specific selections to personalize the character. Alternatively, they can design their own Calling. As an alternate Game Master rule, self-designed Callings might represent Craft or Orphan mages.
</p><p>Perceptive players will notice useful skills are missing on their individual Callings.
</p><p>"Why can't my Dreamspeaker drive a car?"
"I want a Calling that can swim!"
"My character should at least know how to turn on a computer!"
</p><p>What a Game Master can do is allow characters who ought to have certain commonplace real-world skills to make the appropriate Attribute roll without a penalty. In the case of vampires, these skills would be limited to those common at the time of their Embrace, if the time period is widely divergent from when the game itself is set.
</p><p>Here are some sample Callings that represent the Tradition Mages. Each is built on a starting 50 creation point model.
</p>
<ol><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Celestial_Chorus" title="Celestial Chorus">Celestial Chorus</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Order_of_Hermes" title="Order of Hermes">Order of Hermes</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Sons_of_Ether" title="Sons of Ether">Sons of Ether</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Akashic_Brotherhood" title="Akashic Brotherhood">Akashic Brotherhood</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Dreamspeakers" title="Dreamspeakers">Dreamspeakers</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Verbena" title="Verbena">Verbena</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Euthanatos" title="Euthanatos">Euthanatos</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Virtual_Adepts" title="Virtual Adepts">Virtual Adepts</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Cult_of_Ecstasy" title="Cult of Ecstasy">Cult of Ecstasy</a>
</li></ol>
<p>In addition to their calling, all Tradition mages start with:
Lore (Local): +6,
their native Language: +10,
any single Open talent
</p><p>Six Talents in True Magick.
+1 in the corresponding Magick Skill for each level of Sphere Talent (+2 for their Specialty Sphere).
Magic Rating is assigned based on the highest level of Sphere Talent they take (ie: A mage with Life 3 as their highest level will have a MR of 3).
</p><p>Technocracy Callings:
</p>
<ol><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Iteration_X" title="Iteration X">Iteration X</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Void_Engineers" title="Void Engineers">Void Engineers</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/New_World_Order" title="New World Order">New World Order</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Progenitors" title="Progenitors">Progenitors</a>
</li><li> <a href="/wiki/index.php/Syndicate" title="Syndicate">Syndicate</a>
</li></ol>
<p>In addition to their calling, all Technocrat mages start with:
Lore (Local): +6
their native Language: +10
any single Open talent
</p><p>Six Talents in True Magick.
+1 in the corresponding Magick Skill for each level of Sphere Talent (+2 for their Specialty Sphere).
Magic Rating is assigned based on the highest level of Sphere Talent they take (ie: A technocrat with Life 3 as their highest level will have a MR of 3)
</p>
